 :tx/rationale "THE SELF-IMPROVING ACQUISITION FUNCTION: FRONTIER-STEER should not just compute recommendations — it should LEARN from outcomes. Every frontier recommendation is a PREDICTION ('I predict observing materialize/ will yield high information gain'). The next observation IS the outcome (did it produce high surprise? bridge concepts? change F(S)?). The hypothesis ledger already records predictions vs outcomes. Wire frontier recommendations into it: (1) At recommend time: record hypothesis { predicted: 'explore materialize/ yields gain=0.7', boundary: 'coverage', confidence: gain_score }. (2) At next observe time: measure actual gain = surprise of new observation + concept_bridges_formed + delta_F(S). Record as outcome. (3) At harvest time: calibration step adjusts the acquisition weights (connectivity_weight, variance_weight, novelty_weight) via gradient descent on prediction error. (4) Calibrated weights are stored as policy datoms. Transfer via CRDT merge — a team that learned 'connectivity matters more than variance for Go projects' shares it with every Go team. THIS IS THE COMPLETE LEARNING SYSTEM. Three nested loops: (A) OBSERVE loop: single-observation concept assignment + centroid update (SGD). (B) HARVEST loop: crystallization + acquisition weight calibration (batch). (C) CROSS-SESSION loop: calibrated weights in seed + CRDT merge (transfer learning). Each loop operates at a different timescale and optimizes a different level: observations optimize beliefs, harvests optimize ontology, cross-session optimizes the learning algorithm itself. This is the meta-learning architecture — MAML for epistemology."
